# Excalidraw Diagrams

pi-notes should support simple system diagrams as first-class reviewable artifacts.

Local URL: `http://127.0.0.1:4188/notes/resources/excalidraw-diagrams`

## Direction

Use Excalidraw for lightweight architecture, workflow, and graph-shape diagrams.

A local skill now captures the house style:

```text
skills/excalidraw-dag/SKILL.md
```

The style is intentionally narrow: clean DAGs, left-to-right flow, 4–8 boxes, straight arrows, short labels, no decorative sludge.

The first dogfood artifact is:

```text
docs/diagrams/pi-notes-feedback-loop.diagram
```

It diagrams the current browser-to-agent loop:

- Brain pages in `.brain/**/*.svx`
- Document Host rendering SVX
- Review Surface collecting feedback
- Review Batch payloads
- Session Bridge delivery
- Spawned Pi Session source edits
- Review Receipts
- Trace Log

## Product shape

A future pi-notes diagram capability should be boring and useful:

1. Agent creates or updates `.excalidraw` files from project architecture notes.
2. Document Host lists diagrams alongside Brain entries.
3. Browser opens diagrams as readable review artifacts.
4. Review Surface sends comments back to the spawning Pi session.
5. Agents update the diagram file and leave a receipt.

## Boundary

Do not build a full diagram editor inside pi-notes first. Excalidraw already owns editing. pi-notes should own:

- generation
- routing
- review batches
- source-grounded updates
- receipts

## Useful next diagrams

- Document Host / Document Adapter / Review Surface / Session Bridge runtime boundaries
- Review Batch lifecycle state machine
- PARA Brain graph layout
- AI Hero sequence-review adapter pipeline
